          "body": "Verse 14 is the chapter's turning point and its most psychologically penetrating moment. Having just slaughtered 10,000 Edomites and thrown 10,000 more off a cliff, Amaziah returns to Jerusalem and immediately installs the gods of Seir as his own objects of worship. The Chronicler gives no explanation for the impulse — the act stands as a stark data point about the human heart. The prophet's rhetorical question (25:15) makes the absurdity explicit: 'Why have you sought the gods of the people who have not delivered their own people from your hand?' The gods Amaziah worships are gods who just lost. They could not protect their own worshippers from Amaziah's army. Yet Amaziah bows before them and burns incense to them. This is the logic of idolatry as Paul describes it in Romans 1:21-23 — knowing God's power but suppressing that knowledge in exchange for images. Victory should have produced gratitude and deeper dependence on YHWH; instead it produced the spiritual arrogance of a man who believed he had outgrown his need for the God who gave him the win."
